        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         C\xe2\x80\x99mon, Packy. You\xe2\x80\x99re better than this. Writing a blog post about what web3 founders and investors can learn from Jeff Bezos? Jeff Bezos!? Google \xe2\x80\x9cJeff Bezos Business Lessons\xe2\x80\x9d and you\xe2\x80\x99ll get 2.8 million results. This has been done before!
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I know I know, but last week, I got sucked into the old Jeff Bezos interview rabbit hole on YouTube. Two things struck me:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 1em; margin-top: 1em;">
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           The late-90s internet, and the public\xe2\x80\x99s attitude towards it, was strikingly similar to web3, and the public\xe2\x80\x99s attitude towards it, today.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Amazon was the only FAAMG company that was conceived of
           <em>
            explicitly as a business
           </em>
           to take advantage of the internet\xe2\x80\x99s unique characteristics.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Those two observations bounced around in my brain and blobbed into a question:
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          What kind of company would Jeff Bezos start if he were 30 years old today?
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Bezos founded Amazon.com when he was 30 years old, back in 1994. Today, it\xe2\x80\x99s the fifth most valuable company in the world, with a $1.75 trillion market cap. Bezos himself is the richest person in the world and the only one out of the 7.9 billion of us with a net worth over $200 billion. He recently flew to space on his own company\xe2\x80\x99s spaceship. He\xe2\x80\x99s done well, and everyone knows it.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The incredible part of the Amazon story to me, though, is how and why it started.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Other companies have built better business models than Amazon. Google and Facebook are money-printing machines, which Ben Thompson calls
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uhDAMhU8z2Q3KHzQssuim10AmMRAVEiYxrbh9w7CoZMWSn59e_DkgnFM-7Z4KsesZ6NzRRvwtKxJhZkfBPARvRSeNanXPvNVemNawUIYpI24QVkv5QLYf4xocUEjx7eBctmyxo9dO8alrwUujnZcKeyF7wyc3da4Xdy4cPmB0aPEH85kistUuRHt5qM-H_KpVKNfvuqXKjUtbnUguPmqjBZ_l2DE_YZ4zzkAplydE_7yUfJQSIJa6yIKVXAreV6Nsteoa2RihocdRtVwBCqebDgx_jeX10HybZVOOsRC47yuSZRsTjSmHOFf5e4EN17dQTx9q344Y6Bwwwriiv6nQDffNaZgx4nWFH4AqUiWFltpoabqbQsWmha5zrlhN9qm64n_oH9Cfkdc" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Super Aggregators
         </a>
         :
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           What makes Facebook and Google unique is that not only do they have zero transaction costs when it comes to serving end users, they also have zero transaction costs when it comes to both suppliers and advertisers.
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Amazon has to buy and hold physical inventory, build warehouses, create a global logistics network\xe2\x80\xa6 in other words, they deal with atoms. Google and Facebook just deal in bits. But for this exercise, intent matters.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Larry Page, Sergey Brin, and Mark Zuckerberg didn\xe2\x80\x99t set out to build internet behemoths. Google started as a research project, BackRub, that Page and Brin began as Stanford PhD students. Zuck launched Facebook from his Harvard dorm to rate girls.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Bezos, on the other hand, set out with the intention to build a giant business by leveraging the internet\xe2\x80\x99s unique capabilities,
         <em>
          and
         </em>
         was careful to highlight that Amazon was not an internet business. It was a customer business.
         <strong>
          Amazon could only exist because of the internet, but being on the internet wasn\xe2\x80\x99t the value proposition.
         </strong>
         Bezos knew that
         <strong>
          the internet was a tool
         </strong>
         he could use to give customers the things that actually mattered to them: better selection, lower prices, convenience, and a superior customer experience.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         If 30-year-old Jeff Bezos were leaving the hedge fund world to start a business today, chances are, he\xe2\x80\x99d be launching something in web3. It\xe2\x80\x99s growing insanely fast and has the potential to shake everything up enough to create massive, category-defining companies.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I\xe2\x80\x99ve been fully crypto-pilled, and I recognize that my brain is in \xe2\x80\x9chave hammer, look for nails\xe2\x80\x9d mode, but when I watched the four Bezos interviews, both what Bezos said and the way that his interviewers viewed him and Amazon, I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t help but draw comparisons with everything going on in web3 today.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         This is why I can still look myself in the mirror after writing a \xe2\x80\x9cLessons from Jeff Bezos\xe2\x80\x9d post: there\xe2\x80\x99s a lot of Bezos lore that applies to companies at
         <em>
          any
         </em>
         point in time, but
         <strong>
          the stuff we\xe2\x80\x99re covering today only applies in the \xe2\x80\x9ccritical category creation time.\xe2\x80\x9d
         </strong>
         With web3, we\xe2\x80\x99re living through one of those rare times when whole segments will be reshaped and new ones will be created from whole cloth.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Plus, as much fun as the speculative side of crypto is, what really excites me is the new types of businesses and projects that crypto makes possible when you look beyond the hype. I don\xe2\x80\x99t think Bezos would just start a web3 company to start a web3 company. Crypto would be a means, not an end. He\xe2\x80\x99d start something that took advantage of web3\xe2\x80\x99s unique capabilities to better serve customers. He\xe2\x80\x99d likely care a lot more about certain aspects of web3 than most people, and a lot less about other aspects than most people. He would be unafraid to incorporate non-crypto tech, and even atoms, where useful.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The question is, then, what kind of company would he start to take advantage of web3\xe2\x80\x99s unique characteristics to better serve customers and \xe2\x80\x9cbuild a lasting important company born of\xe2\x80\x9d web3?
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The question assumes two things: 1) no one has built a Bezos-esque web3 company to date, and 2) it\xe2\x80\x99s possible to build such a company. The former may be a bad assumption because such a vision may be hiding inside of an unassuming wedge, and the latter may be untrue if web3 is indeed a \xe2\x80\x9c
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhCAMgJ9muK3h12EOHPayr2GqVIesggN1jG-_OB42IS2FNl_6DUA4pXy4NRViZ-joWNFF3MuMRJjZVjB3wTvRSquMfjDvtBfWWBZKN2bEBcLsKG_I1q2fwwAUUvxMcC4Nezrj4T5aozn4Ee7Gyru3hnsUUhnwiBcXNh8wDujwjflIEdnsnkRruanvm_ypZ9_3ZivvZkjLWeVAIU71Jrloa-K2hhHoa82J0pDmUmsWnORS8EdtkkartpGNFRoe2CvDFaAYdNOC5a--vG6aL5NsytYXguH3BLHsYqI-5ROl-e8TFpw_H3XZruZli4GODiP0M_rLA106P2a6CSPmqtl3QFWikkJLbbW07bV3FaWFru9csUr2qU7Ff-gfjCSLag" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          stack with \xe2\x80\x98fat\xe2\x80\x99 protocols and \xe2\x80\x98thin\xe2\x80\x99 applications
         </a>
         .\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Either way, it\xe2\x80\x99s a fun and useful thought exercise and an illuminating trip down memory lane, so we\xe2\x80\x99ll try to answer the question by watching four early Bezos interviews and exploring:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 1em; margin-top: 1em;">
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Critical Category Formation Time
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Early Amazon Ingredients
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            What web3 Does Well
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            WWBB: What Would Bezos Build?
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I\xe2\x80\x99m not as smart as Jeff Bezos, though, so I don\xe2\x80\x99t have the answer. I\xe2\x80\x99ll set the stage and give some guesses, but I\xe2\x80\x99d love to hear what you think as well. Get involved by replying to this tweet:
        </p>
