        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         First, let\xe2\x80\x99s set the stage. Is web3 the kind of tectonic shift that would attract a young Jeff Bezos?
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          Critical Category Formation Time
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The mainstream reaction to Web3 in 2021 feels an awful lot like the reaction to Amazon felt in 1999. That\xe2\x80\x99s hard to really grok until you teleport yourself back to that time.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In hindsight, a company like Amazon seems inevitable. Amazon is Amazon. But even five years into its life, when it was worth $30 billion, the media dismissed it as almost a joke, an overhyped and overvalued futuristic oddity thingamajigger. Its dominance was not a foregone conclusion, or even likely, to anyone outside of Seattle. The way the press talked about Amazon then is the way it talks about crypto now.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Watch this 1999 interview Bezos did with
         <em>
          60 Minutes
         </em>
         :
        </p>
        <a class="youtube-wrap" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkLtqxDAQRb_GKo2etlyoyBICKdKkS2X0mHjF2pJXltb476NdF4FhBu4wc7nH6gxTTIda45bRs435WEEF2LcZcoaEygZp9E6Rjkom-ICc4o5IIZHfxt8EsGg_q5wKoLWY2VudfQyvC4ypQFflhGBS9I72uh-AMs6s7K3oDXH9wI0-fXVxHoIFBQ9IRwyAZnXNed0a9tbQj1r7vrdHLLkYaG1cnorO9tqwj0fD3n8e8itdLuX7_om8opgSPFBMqOCsa2krCdcDGCYw00Asbzst8d1s94bjZaLtVsyWtb09P6OkQswmJh-mur5d9QLza1ETjnUuJfh8jBC0mcGd4fPJ8IVjnCBAqmzdqHMlxyjhlEtOZXeGrXQ44VXHDFVnF-tV-Df9A5o6iAM" rel="" style="display: block; margin: 1.6em 0;" target="_blank">
         <img src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/youtube/w_550,c_limit/l_youtube_play_qyqt8q,w_120/Yv8MrBBuRqI" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; max-width: 550px; vertical-align: middle; width: 100%;"/>
        </a>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Knowing what we know about Amazon now, the interview is cringeworthy. Take, for example, the part in which Bob Simon opines on why Bezos had an unsuccessful dating life in college via voiceover:
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <strong>
           Simon Voiceover:
          </strong>
          Maybe it was his intensity, or maybe it was the way he talks. Listen to the way he describes his company\xe2\x80\x99s business plan.
         </p>
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <strong>
           Bezos: We believe this is a critical category formation time.
          </strong>
         </p>
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <strong>
           Simon Voiceover:
          </strong>
          Bezos uses the same kind of Wall Street wonk talk when he talks or thinks about almost anything.
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         One could imagine
         <em>
          60 Minutes
         </em>
         17.1 million viewers laughing along with Simon at that rich nerd.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         This segment,
         <em>
          Nerd of the Amazon,
         </em>
         was filmed at an in-between time, when Amazon was already a large, public company, but long before its numbers had caught up to its valuation. As Simon said, \xe2\x80\x9cIt lost $125 million last year. The company says it\xe2\x80\x99s investing for the future. Skeptics say,
         <strong>
          it would have to sell every book being sold in the world today to justify its stock price.
         </strong>
         \xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         It\xe2\x80\x99s a well-preserved snapshot of the kind of period that Bezos called a \xe2\x80\x9ccritical category formation time.\xe2\x80\x9d In 1999, the internet was up for grabs, and \xe2\x80\x9celectronic commerce,\xe2\x80\x9d which we just call ecommerce when we call it anything different at all, was a nascent and underdeveloped category. Skeptics rightly pointed out that Amazon\xe2\x80\x99s valuation was crazy based on the reality at the time, but they missed the fact that Amazon would both expand the market and that Amazon itself would do more than just sell books.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Twenty-two years later, Amazon still doesn\xe2\x80\x99t sell every book in the world, but it sells a whole lot more than books, including Amazon Web Services, the main driver of its profits and growth. The company is now worth 60x what it was when the piece was shot in 1999.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Watching that video, the similarities between the general public\xe2\x80\x99s views towards Amazon then and towards crypto today struck me over the head. A good video editor could keep the same quotes, replace a few words, and put out a believable
         <em>
          60 Minutes
         </em>
         piece on crypto today. A few quotes that were particularly reminiscent of the current dialogue:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 1em; margin-top: 1em;">
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           \xe2\x80\x9cWith his computers,
           <strong>
            Bezos used to sell a lot of computer books to computer nerds
           </strong>
           .\xe2\x80\x9d
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           \xe2\x80\x9cA couple of geeks [chuckle] who sketched out some software [chuckle]\xe2\x80\xa6could destroy Sears Roebuck [shakes head].\xe2\x80\x9d
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           \xe2\x80\x9cAt one point on Friday, Amazon.com\xe2\x80\x99s total stock market value surged past $30 billion, making it
           <strong>
            worth more than a major industrial company like Texaco
           </strong>
           [chuckle].\xe2\x80\x9d
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           \xe2\x80\x9cOne of your employees has said that you collect half a gigabyte,
           <strong>
            whatever that is
           </strong>
           , of information on your customers every day. That\xe2\x80\x99s about
           <strong>
            350 floppy disks\xe2\x80\x99 worth
           </strong>
           . What do you
           <em>
            <strong>
             do
            </strong>
           </em>
           with that information?!\xe2\x80\x9d
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           \xe2\x80\x9cIs this investing or is it gambling?\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9cRight now with the frenzy we\xe2\x80\x99ve had, right now
           <strong>
            it feels more like gambling
           </strong>
           .\xe2\x80\x9d
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         See what I mean?
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Now, I admit that there\xe2\x80\x99s survivorship bias here. I could probably go back and find
         <em>
          60 Minutes
         </em>
         features on companies that seemed crazy and ended up failing. Amazon\xe2\x80\x99s ultimate success doesn\xe2\x80\x99t necessarily mean that crypto will succeed. But the similarity in the tone towards Amazon then and the tone towards crypto today is eerie: this is big, and we don\xe2\x80\x99t understand why it\xe2\x80\x99s so big, so let\xe2\x80\x99s cover it, laugh it off, and move on.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I believe we\xe2\x80\x99re in a \xe2\x80\x9ccritical category formation time\xe2\x80\x9d today, too.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Just as Amazon hired away execs from Walmart, Borders, and other major retailers, new people are jumping into web3 daily today.
        </p>
